ğŸ§  Project Overview

This project demonstrates how to deploy a secure, scalable, and cost-effective static website using Amazon Web Services (AWS).
The website is created for Alaghu Nachiamman Traders, a coconut product trading company, and is hosted on an EC2 instance configured with NGINX to serve static content stored in an Amazon S3 bucket.
It integrates HTTPS (SSL) for secure communication and follows real-world DevOps best practices.

ğŸ§± Architecture Diagram

User Browser
     â†“ (https/http)
EC2 Instance (NGINX Reverse Proxy)
     â†“ (config)
Amazon S3 (Static Content)


Workflow:

Users visit the website using EC2 Public IP or domain.
NGINX serves pages from EC2 or fetches static files directly from S3.
HTTPS ensures secure access using SSL certificates.

âš™ï¸ AWS Services Used

Service	Purpose
Amazon EC2	Hosts NGINX web server (reverse proxy).
Amazon S3	Stores static website content (HTML, CSS, JS, images).
IAM Role	Grants EC2 permission to access S3 securely.
NGINX	Serves static files and proxies requests to S3.
Certbot / Letâ€™s Encrypt	Provides free SSL certificates for HTTPS.
AWS CLI	Used for S3 synchronization and automation.

ğŸª£ S3 Configuration

Create an S3 bucket:alaghuwebsite
Region: us-east-1
Disable â€œBlock all public accessâ€
Add public-read policy:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicReadGetObject",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::alaghuwebsite/*"
    }
  ]
}




ğŸ’» EC2 Configuration

Launch EC2 instance:
AMI: Amazon Linux 2
Type: t2.micro (Free Tier)
Security Group:
Port 22 â†’ SSH (Your IP)
Port 80 â†’ HTTP (0.0.0.0/0)
Port 443 â†’ HTTPS (0.0.0.0/0)
Install NGINX:
sudo yum update -y
sudo yum install nginx -y
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx


Verify in browser:

http://<EC2-Public-IP>


You should see the default NGINX welcome page.

ğŸ” NGINX Reverse Proxy Configuration

File: /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name _;

    root /usr/share/nginx/html;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ @s3;
    }

    location @s3 {
        resolver 1.1.1.1;
        proxy_pass https://alaghuwebsite.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com$request_uri;
        proxy_set_header Host alaghuwebsite.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com;
        proxy_hide_header x-amz-id-2;
        proxy_hide_header x-amz-request-id;
    }
}

Restart NGINX:

sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx

ğŸ” Enabling HTTPS (SSL)
âœ… Option 1 â€“ Letâ€™s Encrypt (Recommended)
For domain name (e.g. alaghuwebsite.com):

sudo yum install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d alaghuwebsite.com -d www.alaghuwebsite.com


Automatically:
Generates SSL certificate
Configures NGINX
Sets up auto-renewal (every 90 days)

âš™ï¸ Option 2 â€“ Self-Signed SSL (For Testing with IP)
sudo mkdir /etc/nginx/ssl
sudo openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
-keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/self.key -out /etc/nginx/ssl/self.crt


Add this to /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf:
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name _;

    ssl_certificate     /etc/nginx/ssl/self.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/self.key;

    root /usr/share/nginx/html;
    index index.html;
}


Restart:
sudo systemctl restart nginx

Visit:
https://<EC2-Public-IP>

ğŸ”„ Automate S3 Sync
To auto-update EC2 content from S3 every 10 minutes:
crontab -e
Add:
*/10 * * * * sudo aws s3 sync s3://alaghuwebsite /usr/share/nginx/html/ && sudo systemctl reload nginx

